                <h2>Background: Three Major Efficiency Bottlenecks in Agency Account Opening</h2>
<p>In the process of serving overseas companies, Yiyu Digital Media has identified three high-frequency pain points prevalent in agency account opening businesses:</p>
<p><strong>Information scattered across chat records.</strong> Customer requirements, account opening progress, and recharge records are dispersed across WeChat, emails, spreadsheets, and other tools. Operations staff spend significant time daily "finding information" rather than "handling issues."</p>
<p><strong>Opaque status leads to repeated customer inquiries.</strong> Customers have no visibility into their account progress, and operations has no way to know if upstream agents have responded, resulting in passive waiting.</p>
<p><strong>Over-quota risks are difficult to detect promptly.</strong> A cross-border e-commerce team once experienced a 40% monthly advertising budget overrun due to multi-account recharge amounts exceeding expectations. Post-mortem analysis revealed the lack of a real-time quota monitoring mechanism.</p>
<p>A systematic dashboard is the core tool to address these three issues. Below is the account opening dashboard SOP used internally at Yiyu Digital Media, ready for direct reference and execution.</p>
<h2>SOP Step 1: Define Core Dashboard Fields</h2>
<p>A practical account opening dashboard should include at least the following six fields:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Field Name</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example Values</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Customer Name</td>
<td>Company abbreviation or project code</td>
<td>Certain tool App, Certain home furnishing independent site</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Platform</td>
<td>Meta/TikTok/Google etc.</td>
<td>Meta</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Account Type</td>
<td>Opening/Recharge/Renewal</td>
<td>Opening</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Current Status</td>
<td>Flow node</td>
<td>Materials pending, Submitted, Under review, Live</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Responsible Person</td>
<td>Operations staff name</td>
<td>Zhang San</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Due Date</td>
<td>Customer's expected completion time</td>
<td>2025-02-05</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Key Principle:</strong> Don't overdo the number of fields—keep it to 6-8 maximum. Too many fields will increase the data entry burden on operations staff, and the dashboard will become a burden instead.</p>
<h2>SOP Step 2: Design Status Flow Nodes</h2>
<p>Based on Yiyu Digital Media's experience, the account opening process should have 5-7 status nodes. Too few fails to distinguish progress, while too many increases management costs. Recommended configuration:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Requirements Confirmed</strong>: Customer requirements received, operations begins organizing account opening document checklist</li>
<li><strong>Materials Pending</strong>: Customer hasn't provided complete qualification documents, specific missing items noted</li>
<li><strong>Submitted to Upstream</strong>: Materials sent to primary agent or platform, awaiting feedback</li>
<li><strong>Under Review</strong>: Account under platform review</li>
<li><strong>Account Live</strong>: Account created successfully, entering recharge phase</li>
<li><strong>Recharge Complete</strong>: Funds received, account ready for advertising</li>
<li><strong>Abnormal/Pending</strong>: Special circumstances such as policy restrictions or qualification issues</li>
</ol>
<p>Each status node should have a standard停留时长 (standing time). For example, "Submitted to Upstream" should not exceed 48 hours, and "Under Review" should not exceed 72 hours. The system automatically highlights overdue items in red.</p>
<h2>SOP Step 3: Configure Over-Quota Alert Rules</h2>
<p>This is the most easily overlooked but financially critical aspect. Yiyu Digital Media recommends a dual alert mechanism:</p>
<p><strong>Single Account Quota Alert</strong>: When a single account's monthly recharge amount reaches 80% of the preset threshold, the dashboard automatically changes color and sends a notification. Thresholds are set based on customer historical consumption data; new customers default to 100,000/month.</p>
<p><strong>Team Total Quota Alert</strong>: When all accounts under a customer name approach their monthly budget ceiling, a team-level alert is triggered to prevent overspending.</p>
<p>Alert notifications are recommended via WeCom robots or email to ensure the responsible person receives them promptly.</p>
<h2>SOP Step 4: Establish Periodic Review Mechanisms</h2>
<p>After building the dashboard, continuous maintenance is crucial. Yiyu Digital Media internally implements a "Daily Check + Weekly Review" system:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Daily Check</strong> (approx. 10 minutes): Operations staff checks their assigned cards at the start of the workday, confirming no abnormal stuck items or overdue tasks</li>
<li><strong>Weekly Review</strong> (approx. 30 minutes): Team leader pulls weekly account opening time distribution, over-quota alert frequency, and customer complaint reason summaries to identify process bottlenecks and optimize</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<p>A home furnishing independent site customer once complained about lengthy account opening cycles. Post-mortem revealed the "Materials Pending" phase averaged 4.2 days, the main cause of extended overall cycles. Subsequent implementation of advance document checklists and customer pre-review mechanisms compressed this phase to 1.5 days.</p>
</blockquote>
<h2>SOP Step 5: Tool Selection Recommendations</h2>
<p>For small-to-medium teams (3-10 people), the following tool combinations are recommended:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Lightweight</strong>: Notion or Feishu Multi-dimensional Tables, zero cost to get started, supports real-time multi-person collaboration</li>
<li><strong>Advanced</strong>: Monday.com or Jira, more comprehensive features, supports custom automation rules</li>
<li><strong>Integration Needs</strong>: If financial system connectivity is required, using Zapier to sync dashboard data to financial reconciliation spreadsheets is recommended</li>
</ul>
<p>The tool doesn't need to be "advanced"—what matters is whether the team can stick with it. Choose the one with the lowest learning curve.</p>
<h2>Closing</h2>
<p>The essence of a systematic dashboard is transforming from "memory-based management" to "process-based management." For operations teams handling 10+ account opening requests daily, the dashboard is not optional—it's essential. It cannot eliminate all problems, but it can expose them earlier and enable faster responses.</p>
<p>For Yiyu Digital Media's account opening dashboard templates or one-on-one consultation, please contact our operations team.</p>
